body:
I was able to replicate your issue with this model [vocoder.onnx](https://huggingface.co/npc-engine/exported-flowtron-waveglow-librispeech-tts/blob/main/vocoder.onnx) and the following code:

```python
import numpy
import pandas
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from onnxruntime import InferenceSession
from mlprodict.onnxrt import OnnxInference

def profile_plot(df, size=(12, 4)):
    gr_dur = df[['dur', "args_op_name"]].groupby("args_op_name").sum().sort_values('dur')
    gr_n = df[['dur', "args_op_name"]].groupby("args_op_name").count().sort_values('dur')
    gr_n = gr_n.loc[gr_dur.index, :]

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=size)
    gr_dur.plot.barh(ax=ax[0])
    gr_n.plot.barh(ax=ax[1])
    ax[0].set_title("duration")
    ax[1].set_title("n occurences");
    return df, ax

def profile(filename):
    x = numpy.random.random([1, 80, 10]).astype(numpy.float32)
    oinf = OnnxInference(filename, runtime="onnxruntime1",
                         runtime_options={"enable_profiling": True})
    for i in range(0, 10):
        oinf.run({"mels": x})
    df = oinf.get_profiling(as_df=True)
    return df

df1 = profile("vocoder.onnx")
df2 = profile("vocoder_uint8.onnx")
df2["args_op_name"] = df2["args_op_name"] + "-Q"
df = pandas.concat([df1, df2], axis=0)
profile_plot(df, size=(14, 8));
```

It gives the following results:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22452781/188454034-fefc18c3-3c2c-4f3d-a260-0971f4090409.png)

ConvInteger is slow than Conv on this particular example. I compare the input sizes. First model:

| shape                     |              dur |
|:--------------------------|-----------------:|
| 1x256x320@512x256x3@512   |      3.05178e+06 |
| 1x640x320@4096x640x1@4096 |      2.34432e+06 |
| 1x256x320@512x256x1@512   | 933696           |
| 1x256x320@256x256x1@256   |  69256           |
| 1x2x320@256x2x1@256       |   5858           |

Second model:

| shape                |              dur |
|:---------------------|-----------------:|
| 1x256x320@512x256x3  |      6.29231e+06 |
| 1x640x320@4096x640x1 |      1.88803e+06 |
| 1x256x320@512x256x1  | 750161           |
| 1x256x320@256x256x1  |  53866           |
| 1x2x320@256x2x1      |   4132           |

It needs more investigation.

Thank you, xadupre.
I will profile the two TTS models tomorrow and give out the exact profiler outputs. (Although I think few efforts can be made to accelerate the inference speed based on the current CPU.
@yufenglee Is there a known reason why the ConvInteger nodes in a dynamically quantized model are taking longer than Conv Nodes in the original fp32 model?

The profile result shows the ConvInteger nodes cost a lot of time.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/59953951/188590933-a89a4851-f3f8-4528-bbc9-0784e30c231d.png)

I looked into the code. ConvInteger is using im2col + qgemm. Conv<float> (and only float) has a specific implementation. I'm wondering if the quantized version is faster in some cases or always slower.

It is recommended to use static quantization for CNN based models and we don't have special performance optimization on ConvInteger yet. Please refer to the doc here: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/performance/quantization.html#method-selection.

@jchen351 is working on consolidating ConvInteger and QLinearConv. Once it is done, perf of ConvInteger will be improved.
@yufenglee thanks~ I'll try the static quantize method. Hope it works. I will give out the static quant result later.

issue.title: [Performance] Relative time gains from dynamic quantization decrease over the number of CPU cores used (CPUExecutionProvider)

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
### Describe the issue

As seen below, relative gains from quantization seem to decrease with the number of physical CPU cores used. I would be curious to know why.

A second issue is that quantizing Conv (passing as well with `weights_dtype=QUInt8`) layers actually hurt time performances, this could be related to https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/12854 and is an other issue than the one addressed here.

![ncores_c6i](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9808326/189612771-4327013a-d390-4a98-a30a-94c7feaa6f14.png)


### To reproduce

This was done on an AWS EC2 c6i instance, using only the physical cores 0-7.

Typically, in order to pin onnxruntime to specific CPU ids, e.g. 0-3, I do: `taskset -c 0-3 benchmark_script.py`, and set `intra_op_num_threads = 4` within the session options. In this example, we verify with `mpstat` that indeed only the requested CPU ids are used.

The full script is not reproduced here, but the main piece is here: https://github.com/huggingface/optimum/blob/9b0474973cecbf15f1ba8280e2d0f25f5e8c4021/optimum/runs_base.py#L189-L282

I use a batch size of 1, and run the benchmark for 15 seconds.

Model used: https://huggingface.co/fxmarty/levit-256-onnx

### Urgency

Not urgent

### Platform

Linux

### OS Version

Ubuntu 22.04 jammy, x86_64 Linux 5.15.0-47-generic

### ONNX Runtime Installation

Released Package

### ONNX Runtime Version or Commit ID

1.12.1

### ONNX Runtime API

Python

### Architecture

X64

### Execution Provider

Default CPU

### Execution Provider Library Version

_No response_

### Model File

_No response_

### Is this a quantized model?

Yes
